    <item>
      <title>Harris's VP pick former Rep. Tim Walz: His most interesting bills in Congress - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://govtrack.us/posts/437/2024-08-07_harriss-vp-pick-former-rep-tim-walz-his-most-interesting-bills-in-congress</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://govtrack.us/posts/437/2024-08-07_harriss-vp-pick-former-rep-tim-walz-his-most-interesting-bills-in-congress</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;Harris&amp;#39;s VP pick former Rep. Tim Walz: His most interesting bills in Congress&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Analysis and Commentary Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Aug 7, 2024           &amp;middot; by Jesse Rifkin       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;p&gt;Before Democratic presidential nominee Kamala Harris chose him as her running mate on Tuesday, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/timothy_walz/412214"&gt;Tim Walz&lt;/a&gt; served 12 years in the U.S. House of Representatives from 2007 to 2018. Here are eight of the most interesting bills he introduced, including some of his &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?sponsor=412214#current_status%5B%5D=28"&gt;bills which were enacted into law&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz's bills almost entirely focused on veterans' health care and employment, many of which had bipartisan support. He also introduced bills to limit stock trading by legislators and corporations' spending on elections, bills to promote energy independence and green energy, and bills on agricultural issues that wouldn't make national headlines including &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr5188"&gt;farm soil health&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Three weeks ago, GovTrack also analyzed eight of the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/431/2024-07-17_trumps-vp-pick-sen-jd-vance-his-most-interesting-bills-in-congress"&gt;most interesting bills Republican vice presidential nominee J.D. Vance introduced&lt;/a&gt; in the Senate. The contrast between Walz and Vance goes beyond the obvious ideology differences. Vance's bills largely dealt with "red meat" social and culture-war issues, such as immigration, affirmative action, race, and transgender issues. ("Red meat" issues are divisive issues that are intended to energize a politician's base.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;All five enacted bills for which Walz served as lead sponsor dealt with military or veteran issues. The first three bills below were among them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This was personal for Walz, who &lt;a href="https://mn.gov/governor/about-gov/timwalz/"&gt;served in the National Guard for 24 years&lt;/a&gt;, rising to the rank of &lt;a href="https://taskandpurpose.com/news/walz-vp-pick-enlisted/#:%7E:text=In%20his%20final%20assignment%2C%20Walz,spokesperson%20for%20the%20Minnesota%20National"&gt;command sergeant major&lt;/a&gt;. He also served as &lt;a href="https://veterans.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=549"&gt;ranking member on the House Veterans' Affairs Committee&lt;/a&gt; in 2017-18, when Republicans controlled the chamber. (Vance also served in the military, deploying to Iraq with the Marines, where he &lt;a href="https://taskandpurpose.com/news/jd-vance-marine-veteran/"&gt;rose to the rank of corporal&lt;/a&gt;. But contrasted with Walz, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?sponsor=456876&amp;amp;subject=5852"&gt;almost none of Vance's Senate bills deal with military or veteran issues&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr203"&gt;Clay Hunt Suicide Prevention for American Veterans Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Clay Hunt, a Marine veteran from Houston who served in Afghanistan and Iraq, &lt;a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-life-and-death-of-clay-hunt/"&gt;died by suicide in 2011&lt;/a&gt;. He was only &lt;a href="https://people.com/celebrity/american-sniper-clay-hunts-tragic-suicide/"&gt;28&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Unfortunately, his situation wasn't an aberration. &lt;a href="https://www.mentalhealth.va.gov/docs/data-sheets/2023/2023-National-Veteran-Suicide-Prevention-Annual-Report-FINAL-508.pdf#page=8"&gt;6,392 veterans died by suicide&lt;/a&gt; in 2021, the most recent year available, marking a slight increase over the year prior.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2015, Walz introduced Hunt's namesake bill to reform several aspects of VA mental health care:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr203/text/enr#link=2&amp;amp;nearest=HC683DE6C7CFA42F78A4C99C319B89077"&gt;Conducting&lt;/a&gt; annual evaluations of its mental health care and suicide prevention programs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr203/text/enr#link=3&amp;amp;nearest=HBB7E1A08C59D45AC97641C64EDBF4E8D"&gt;Creating&lt;/a&gt; a website about its mental health services.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr203/text/enr#link=4&amp;amp;nearest=H67CE305C479243B5A621FF4753121C62"&gt;Establishing&lt;/a&gt; a pilot program for repaying student loans of VA staff psychiatrists.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr203/text/enr#link=7&amp;amp;nearest=H8112D9639EE3463C9F1D2B6C0850B2E0"&gt;Extending&lt;/a&gt; the eligibility period for health care services for veterans who served during certain periods.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Veterans die by suicide each and every day," &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160907063935/http://walz.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/walz-miller-duckworth-reintroduce-clay-hunt-sav-act-to-address-veteran"&gt;Walz said in a 2015 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "While no piece of legislation will completely end this heartbreaking epidemic, we cannot stand idly by while more of our heroes struggle with the invisible wounds of war."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House passed it unanimously &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/h17"&gt;403-0&lt;/a&gt;, then the Senate followed suit by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/s50"&gt;99-0&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/john_mccain/300071"&gt;Then-Sen. John McCain (R-AZ)&lt;/a&gt;, a Vietnam veteran himself, sponsored the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/s167"&gt;Senate version&lt;/a&gt;. President Barack Obama signed it into law.Â &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If you or somebody you know is experiencing thoughts of suicide, call the toll-free hotline 988, available 24 hours a day.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr3670"&gt;Reforming TSA hiring practices for veterans&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Years before Walz was elected, Congress enacted the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/103/hr995"&gt;Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act (USERRA) of 1994&lt;/a&gt;. The law guarantees enlisted military members called up to active duty retain their preexisting benefits and seniority once they return to their civilian jobs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But after the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks, Congress created the Transportation Security Administration (TSA), which needed to surge its staffing quickly. So the nascent agency was granted an exemption from the 1994 law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;By 2012, Walz believed the TSA's original early-2000s exemption was no longer needed. Indeed, even the TSA itself agreed, since they'd &lt;a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CRPT-112hrpt487/html/CRPT-112hrpt487-pt1.htm"&gt;voluntarily returned to compliance with the 1994 law by that time&lt;/a&gt;. However, this voluntary change still wasn't actually guaranteed by law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"The unemployment rate among our service members is already far too high. Protecting the jobs they already have should be a top priority," &lt;a href="https://bilirakis.house.gov/media/press-releases/bilirakis-owens-walz-bipartisan-legislation-passes-house-expand-job-protection"&gt;Walz said in a 2012 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "[This] bill simply ensures that the thousands of veterans, reservists, and members of the National Guard working for TSA are protected as they would be in any other position."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House passed it by voice vote, then the Senate passed it by unanimous consent. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/joseph_lieberman/300067"&gt;Then-Sen. Joe Lieberman (I-CT)&lt;/a&gt; sponsored the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/s1990"&gt;Senate version&lt;/a&gt;. President Obama signed it into law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr1725"&gt;Quicker Veterans Benefits Delivery Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz introduced a bill mandating the VA submit two annual reports about medical treatment for veterans, in hopes of speeding up wait times and eliminating unnecessary or duplicative examinations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz's original version actually would have included direct public policy effects, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr1725/text/ih#link=2&amp;amp;nearest=H2837ED48B0B44FA288ACDE312B72472A"&gt;allowing local non-VA doctors to conduct disability medical examinations for veterans&lt;/a&gt;. However, that provision was omitted from the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr1725/text"&gt;final enacted version&lt;/a&gt;, which only mandated two annual reports.Â &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Our goal with this legislation is simple: to uphold the promises we've made to our veterans by ending the backlog and getting them the benefits they have earned and deserve," &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/115/meeting/house/105843/witnesses/HHRG-115-VR09-Wstate-W000799-20170405.pdf#page=3"&gt;Walz said in a 2017 statement to the House Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs&lt;/a&gt;. "This is a common sense solution that will aid in adding efficiency to a complicated process in order to better serve our nation's heroes."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House passed it by voice vote, then the Senate passed it by unanimous consent. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/alan_franken/412378"&gt;Then-Sen. Al Franken (D-MN)&lt;/a&gt; introduced &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/s706"&gt;the Senate version&lt;/a&gt;. President Donald Trump signed it into law in March 2018.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;(Franken &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/files/20180412_R44781_2ae22d84a1afb9a470a0ab2ea0128ee49fbd9d8e.pdf#page=6"&gt;resigned his Senate seat in January 2018&lt;/a&gt; after sexual harassment allegations, so he was no longer serving by the time his own legislation was enacted.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr1148"&gt;STOCK (Stop Trading on Congressional Knowledge) Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2011, &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2zh30lm7aSQ"&gt;CBS's 60 Minutes revealed&lt;/a&gt; how Congress members legally used non-public information gleaned from closed committee hearings when buying and selling stocks. Walz had previously introduced a bill to ban the practice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He actually introduced it in March that year, several months before  &lt;a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/congress-trading-stock-on-inside-information/"&gt;the investigative report that November&lt;/a&gt;. Sorting cosponsors by the date they joined, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr1148/cosponsors"&gt;only 10 of the eventual 286&lt;/a&gt; added their names before the report aired on November 13.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"The same standards we have established for Wall Street should apply to Congress," &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20110407000935/http://walz.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&amp;amp;view=article&amp;amp;id=326:walz-and-slaughter-say-legislation-is-needed-to-curb-congressional-insider-trading&amp;amp;catid=7:latest-news"&gt;Walz said in a 2011 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "The potential for abuse is obvious and troubling, and there is simply no good reason Congress should get to play by a separate set of rules in the stock market."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Some Republicans argued it violated Congress members' freedoms, while some Democrats contended the bill wasn't strong enough, in particular the mere &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/06/06/nx-s1-4974720/congress-stock-trades-profits"&gt;$200 fine for a first-time offense&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In response to the exposÃ©, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/joseph_lieberman/300067"&gt;Sen. Joe Lieberman (I-CT)&lt;/a&gt; introduced &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/s2038"&gt;a similar bill&lt;/a&gt; which passed the Senate &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/112-2012/s14"&gt;96-3&lt;/a&gt; and the House &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/112-2012/h47"&gt;417-2&lt;/a&gt;. The two chambers ironed out their differences in conference. President Obama signed it into law, but a year later Congress and Obama &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2013/04/16/177496734/how-congress-quietly-overhauled-its-insider-trading-law"&gt;quietly rolled back some of the provisions&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Where is it today?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While the STOCK Act banned Congress members from buying or selling stocks based on non-public information, it didn't ban them from trading stocks entirely. In the current Congress, several bipartisan bills would do just that, though none have yet received a committee vote:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1679"&gt;Bipartisan Ban on Congressional Stock Ownership Act&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/pramila_jayapal/412730"&gt;Rep. Pramila Jayapal (D-WA7)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr3003"&gt;Bipartisan Restoring Faith in Government Act&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/brian_fitzpatrick/412721"&gt;Rep. Brian Fitzpatrick (R-PA1)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr6842"&gt;STOCK Act 2.0&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/katie_porter/412758"&gt;Rep. Katie Porter (D-CA47)&lt;/a&gt; in the House and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/kirsten_gillibrand/412223"&gt;Sen. Kirsten Gillibrand (D-NY)&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s3555"&gt;Senate&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s2463"&gt;Ban Stock Trading for Government Officials Act&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/joshua_hawley/412840"&gt;Sen. Josh Hawley (R-MO)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr5520"&gt;VA Medicinal Cannabis Research Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Medical marijuana is now &lt;a href="https://disa.com/marijuana-legality-by-state"&gt;legal in 37 states plus the District of Columbia&lt;/a&gt;. However, it remains illegal at the federal level, where the drug is classified as &lt;a href="https://www.dea.gov/drug-information/drug-scheduling"&gt;Schedule I&lt;/a&gt;, grouped in the same strongest category as heroin and meth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As a result, the VA as a federal healthcare provider &lt;a href="https://www.publichealth.va.gov/marijuana.asp"&gt;can't prescribe medical marijuana for its veteran patients&lt;/a&gt; suffering from conditions like PTSD (post-traumatic stress disorder).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz introduced a bill to allow the VA to "conduct and support research on the efficacy and safety of medicinal cannabis" -- essentially, to even permit an official study for the first time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"We have all heard the stories of veterans who have used cannabis medicinally to cope with physical and psychological injuries sustained during their service to our country," &lt;a href="https://democrats-veterans.house.gov/news/press-releases/committee-leaders-introduce-bipartisan-va-medicinal-cannabis-research-act-2018"&gt;Walz said in a 2018 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "While we know cannabis can have life-saving effects on veterans suffering from chronic pain or PTSD, there has been a severe lack of research studying the full effect of medicinal cannabis on these veterans."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bill attracted 55 bipartisan cosponsors, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr5520/cosponsors"&gt;44 Democrats and 11 Republicans&lt;/a&gt;. The House Veterans' Affairs Committee approved it, but it never received a vote in the full chamber.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Opponents generally oppose marijuana legalization in any form, whether at the state or federal level. "When the conversation about how to serve our veterans after all they sacrificed is to give them marijuana --- we have failed our veterans," &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/james_lankford/412464"&gt;Sen. James Lankford (R-OK)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://x.com/SenatorLankford/status/1651222544962166784"&gt;posted on X to explain his opposition&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Where is it today?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/luis_correa/412688"&gt;Rep. Luis Correa (D-CA46)&lt;/a&gt; has picked up the mantle since Walz left Congress, introducing the House bill in &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hr712"&gt;2019&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/117/hr2916"&gt;2021&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1003"&gt;2023&lt;/a&gt;. The 2019 and 2021 versions were passed in committee, but never received votes in the full chamber.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/jon_tester/412244"&gt;Sen. Jon Tester (D-MT)&lt;/a&gt; introduced the original &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/s2796"&gt;Senate version&lt;/a&gt; alongside Walz and has continued to reintroduce it every Congress since.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s326"&gt;2023 Senate version&lt;/a&gt; became the first to receive a vote in the upper chamber. It failed on a cloture vote, an attempt to break a filibuster. While it won majority support by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2023/s97"&gt;57-42&lt;/a&gt;, that fell short of the three-fifths required. Democrats unanimously supported it, while Republicans largely opposed it 8-41.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In May, the Justice Department &lt;a href="https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/justice-department-submits-proposed-regulation-reschedule-marijuana"&gt;announced a proposal to downgrade marijuana from Schedule I to Schedule III&lt;/a&gt;. As of this writing, that change has not been finalized. Even if it is, though, the drug would remain illegal on a federal level -- just with more lenient penalties. So Congress would still have to enact legislation to let the VA prescribe medical marijuana.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/111/hr3787"&gt;Honor America's Guard-Reserve Retirees Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Military members who served in the National Guard or Reserves, but were never called up to active duty, are not considered "veterans" under federal law. Walz's bill would have granted them veteran status if they'd served at least 20 years.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"These men and women took an oath to defend our nation at any cost and have dedicated their lives in service to our country," &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120927232539/http://walz.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&amp;amp;task=view&amp;amp;id=366&amp;amp;Itemid=25"&gt;Walz said in a 2011 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "This is about giving them the honor and recognition they deserve."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Opponents included the VA itself, countering that the existing definition exists for a reason.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"VA recognizes that the National Guard and Reserves have admirably served this country and in recent years have played an important role in our nation's overseas conflicts," David McLenachen, VA's Acting Deputy Under Secretary for Disability Assistance, &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150804014658/http://veterans.house.gov/witness-testimony/mr-david-r-mclenachen-1"&gt;said in House committee testimony in 2015&lt;/a&gt;. "Nevertheless, VA does not support this bill because it represents a departure from active service as the foundation for veteran status."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz reintroduced the bill in four consecutive Congress, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/111/hr3787/cosponsors"&gt;attracting&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr1025/cosponsors"&gt;steadily&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr679/cosponsors"&gt;more&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr1384/cosponsors"&gt;cosponsors&lt;/a&gt; each time. It passed the House three of those four times: in 2009 and 2011 by voice vote, then in 2015 unanimously by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/h628"&gt;407-0&lt;/a&gt;. However, the Senate never took it up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Where is it today?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Most National Guard or Reserves members who were never called up to active duty are still &lt;a href="https://www.va.gov/OSDBU/docs/Determining-Veteran-Status.pdf#page=3"&gt;not considered veterans&lt;/a&gt;. (Rare exemptions are granted for those who became disabled because of an injury incurred as part of their role, for example during military training.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;GovTrack was &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?congress=__ALL__&amp;amp;text=%22Honor%20America%E2%80%99s%20Guard-Reserve%20Retirees%20Act%22#sort=-introduced_date&amp;amp;congress=__ALL__"&gt;unable to locate any subsequent version of the bill introduced by another member of Congress&lt;/a&gt; after Walz left.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/111/hr4617"&gt;Separate Taxpayer Dollars from the Election Process Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;2010's Supreme Court decision &lt;a href="https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/ll/usrep/usrep558/usrep558310/usrep558310.pdf"&gt;Citizens United v. FEC&lt;/a&gt; allowed unlimited independent political campaign spending by corporations and unions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Overturning the decision entirely would take a constitutional amendment. Indeed, Walz cosponsored three unsuccessful constitutional amendments from &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/theodore_deutch/412385"&gt;Rep. Ted Deutch (D-FL22)&lt;/a&gt; to do just that, in &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hjres119/cosponsors"&gt;2014&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hjres22/cosponsors"&gt;2015&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hjres31"&gt;2017&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But Walz also introduced a smaller and more targeted proposal, which only required a bill rather than a constitutional amendment.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;During the 2008 financial crash, Congress created the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP) to bail out major financial institutions. Walz's bill would have prevented those corporations specifically from spending money on campaigns or elections.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It was wrong that American taxpayers had to bail out Wall Street banks for their reckless behavior," &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100321081939/http://walz.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&amp;amp;view=article&amp;amp;id=240:walz-introduces-bill-to-prevent-wall-street-banks-from-using-taxpayer-qbailout-dollarsq-to-influence-the-outcome-of-us-elections&amp;amp;catid=7:latest-news"&gt;Walz said in a 2010 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "It is outrageous these same Wall Street banks can now use your taxpayer money to run TV attack ads attempting to elect or defeat candidates for public office."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Opponents counter that the Supreme Court decision protected free speech and political advocacy, a liberty at the very heart of American rights.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"While it is true that some for-profit corporations have great amounts of wealth at their disposal, most of the several million corporations in the United States lack the financial wherewithal to corrupt officeholders," &lt;a href="https://www.scotusblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/Citizens-United-CU-Supplemental-Reply-Brief.pdf#page=9"&gt;the titular organization Citizens United wrote in their Supreme Court brief&lt;/a&gt;. "In that sense, corporations are reflective of America's individuals."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Where is it today?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz's bill attracted no cosponsors and never received a vote in either the House Administration or Financial Services Committees, even though Democrats controlled the chamber at the time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;TARP &lt;a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ally-financial-exits-tarp-as-treasury-sells-remaining-stake-1419000430"&gt;effectively ended in December 2014&lt;/a&gt;, when the federal government sold its last shares of Ally Financial, the last remaining institution covered by the program.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/110/hr2691"&gt;Wind Energy Promotion Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz introduced a bill making it easier to qualify for federal wind energy tax credits, which could have brought more money to the clean energy industry &lt;a href="https://cleangridalliance.org/blog/80/minnesota-renewable-energy-job-growth-is-the-focus-of-new-report-and-case-study"&gt;booming in Walz's home state of Minnesota&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Raising capital for wind energy projects is difficult, because many residents of rural America do not qualify for the Renewable Energy Production Tax Credit (PTC), which is one of the major incentives to promote wind energy production," &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20070613015211/http://www.walz.house.gov/News/DocumentSingle.aspx?DocumentID=67417"&gt;Walz said in a 2007 press release&lt;/a&gt;. "This legislation will... [level] the playing field for individuals in rural America who are looking to enter the industry."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Opponents counter that wind turbines "kill all the birds," &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/07/15/jd-vance-agenda-policies-00168467"&gt;Vance said at a June speech to the Turning Point Action conference&lt;/a&gt;, even though research found they kill &lt;a href="https://climate.mit.edu/ask-mit/do-wind-turbines-kill-birds"&gt;20 times fewer&lt;/a&gt; birds than fossil fuel energy.Â  "And they're mostly made in China," he added, though that &lt;a href="https://energydigital.com/top10/top-10-wind-turbine-manufacturers"&gt;may not be true either&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Walz introduced the bill twice. His 2007 version attracted eight bipartisan cosponsors, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/110/hr2691/cosponsors"&gt;six Democrats and two Republicans&lt;/a&gt;, but never received a House Ways and Means Committee vote. His 2009 version attracted nine bipartisan cosponsors: &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/111/hr3135/cosponsors"&gt;eight Democrats and one Republican&lt;/a&gt;, but again never received a committee vote.Â &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;However, 2009's Democratic-controlled Congress enacted the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/111/hr1"&gt;American Recovery and Reinvestment Act&lt;/a&gt; -- often nicknamed "the stimulus" -- which included &lt;a href="https://www.energy.gov/recovery-act"&gt;$31 billion in renewable energy incentives and investments&lt;/a&gt;. Walz voted for that legislation, as did &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/111-2009/h70"&gt;all but seven House Democrats&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As governor, Walz has &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/06/climate/tim-walz-climate-change.html"&gt;focused on climate issues&lt;/a&gt;, declaring a state goal of 100% clean or renewable energy by 2040. He signed his most recent state energy legislation in June &lt;a href="https://mn.gov/governor/newsroom/press-releases/?id=1055-630240"&gt;at a wind farm in Dexter, Minnesota&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
