      <title>Breaks in the Pattern - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://govtrack.us/posts/433/2024-07-26_breaks-in-the-pattern</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://govtrack.us/posts/433/2024-07-26_breaks-in-the-pattern</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;Breaks in the Pattern&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Legislative Recap Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Jul 26, 2024           &amp;middot; by Amy West       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;p&gt;Over the course of this Congress, several patterns have emerged:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;extremely small numbers of Republicans will object to legislation the rest of the Republicans want and thus kill the legislation&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;for those bills that the majority of the House - Republican and Democrat - want, leadership will bring the bills to the floor "under suspension" meaning it needs 2/3rd majority to pass and they do, easily&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;partisan messaging bills that will pass narrowly on a party line or, if in some way related to immigration / border enforcement, with a small number of Democrats&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;While the pattern held over all this last week before the very long summer recess, there were some interesting breaks in it too.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Appropriations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;This week House leadership &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/live-updates/2024/07/22/congress/gop-pulls-funding-bills-00170361"&gt;pulled their bills for Agriculture and the FDA, and financial services&lt;/a&gt;, because they didn't have the votes within the Republican membership. Basically, some Republicans thought the bills were too conservative because they contained various anti-abortion provisions and others thought they weren't conservative enough because they didn't cut spending enough. Since it only takes three members to vote no to sink the bills, both were pulled.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then they spent a good bit of time on amendments to &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8997"&gt;H.R. 8997: Energy and Water Development and Related Agencies Appropriations Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; before pulling it from the floor too. Amendments that passed included:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;H.Amdt. 1099 (Ogles) to H.R. 8997: To prohibit funding for the American Climate Corps which passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h363"&gt;199-197&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;H.Amdt. 1114 (Rosendale) to H.R. 8997: To prevent funds from being used to transfer or delegate control or maintenance responsibility of the Lower Yellowstone Fish Bypass Channel to any non-Federal entity which passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h374"&gt;218-204&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;H.Amdt. 1122 (Van Drew) to H.R. 8997: To move $10,000,000 from renewable energy programs to enhance the security of existing electrical transformers from cyber threats and from physical attacks from individuals which passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h379"&gt;214-203&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;One bill did survive to break the pattern above:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8998"&gt;H.R. 8998: Department of the Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies Appropriations Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; and passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h399"&gt;210-205&lt;/a&gt;. It had two successful amendments:&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;H.Amdt. 1145 (Brecheen) to H.R. 8998: To prohibit funding for any diversity, equity, and inclusion program or office which passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h388"&gt;211-202&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;H.Amdt. 1170 (Perry) to H.R. 8998: To prohibit funds made available by this Act to be used for environmental justice activities which passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h397"&gt;210-204&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Bills on Suspension&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hres1367"&gt;H.Res. 1367: Establishing the Task Force on the Attempted Assassination of Donald J. Trump&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h393"&gt;416-0&lt;/a&gt;. Membership is still being determined.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s3706"&gt;S. 3706: Victimsâ VOICES Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h361"&gt;408-2&lt;/a&gt;. This bill would allow someone acting on behalf of a victim of crime to receive restitution. The only no votes were from two Republicans. It goes to the President next.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s227"&gt;S. 227: Improving Access to Our Courts Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h362"&gt;404-3&lt;/a&gt;. The only no votes were three Republicans who voted against adding two new physical locations in which court must be held in Texas and Washington districts. It goes to the President next.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8812/summary"&gt;H.R. 8812: Water Resources Development Act of 2024&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h358"&gt;359-13&lt;/a&gt;. This bill "authorizes, deauthorizes, and modifies various water resources feasibility studies and projects of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;Here's the other break in the pattern: two bills on suspension failed:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1631"&gt;H.R. 1631: Pro Codes Act&lt;/a&gt; failed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h357"&gt;248-127&lt;/a&gt;. This bill would give private entities that produce codes referenced in laws - like building codes - copyright protection provided those entities make the codes freely available online. However, the burden of pursuing those entities if they did not put the codes on the web for free would fall to others. This vote was unusual in another way: there wasn't an immediately obvious pattern to who voted yes or no and a large number of members (56) didn't vote at all.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7887/summary"&gt;H.R. 7887: ACCESS Act&lt;/a&gt; failed on suspension by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h380"&gt;178-234&lt;/a&gt;. It would have failed on a regular vote too with all Democrats voting against along with 35 Republicans. The bill would have prohibited requirements for minimum experience or education in federal solicitations unless the agency specifically explained why such minimums were required.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Nominations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/s214"&gt;Colleen Duffy Kiko, of North Dakota, to be a Member of the Federal Labor Relations Authority for a term of five years expiring July 29, 2027&lt;/a&gt; passed the Senate 82-6&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Partisan Messaging&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;As its last act before leaving for six weeks, the House voted on&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hres1371"&gt;H.Res. 1371: Strongly condemning the Biden Administration and its Border Czar, Kamala Harrisâs, failure to secure the United States border&lt;/a&gt;. It passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h400"&gt;220-196&lt;/a&gt; with six Democrats voting in favor. Those Democrats are all in otherwise right-leaning districts and they have consistently been voting in favor of Republican bills regarding border issues all year long.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;The title is incorrect - &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2021/03/24/remarks-by-president-biden-and-vice-president-harris-in-a-meeting-on-immigration/"&gt;Harris was given responsibility 2021 for diplomacy with nations from which many folks arriving at the border come&lt;/a&gt; in order to try to make staying in their home countries more attractive and viable. Responsibility for managing the US borders belongs to the &lt;a href="https://www.dhs.gov/topics/secretary-homeland-security"&gt;Department of Homeland Security&lt;/a&gt;. The text of the resolution, which has no legal force, was amended to accurately describe Harris's responsibilities and (largely) Republican dissatisfaction with how the Biden Administration has managed migrants arriving at the border.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Scheduling note&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;With Congress out until September 9th, we'll be using the interim to address more of the questions we've received and, as always, feel free to let us know if you've got one burning you'd like answered.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
